edu.first.util.list

Interface Collection

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    List
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ArrayList, SafeArrayList, SortedArrayList

    public interface Collection
extends Iterable
    A collection represents a group of objects, known as its elements. Some collections allow duplicate elements and others do not. Some are ordered and others unordered. This interface is typically used to pass collections around and manipulate them where maximum generality is desired.
    Since:

      • contains

        boolean contains(java.lang.Object o)
        Returns whether this collection contains o. Returns true if and only if there is one element that o.equals(element) || (o == null && element == null).
        Parameters:
        o - element whose presence in this collection is to be tested
        Returns:
        if this collection contains the specified element

      • toArray

        java.lang.Object[] toArray()
        Returns an array containing all of the elements in this collection. The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by this collection. (In other words, this method must allocate a new array even if this collection is backed by an array). The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.
        Returns:
        an array containing all of the elements in this collection

      • add

        void add(java.lang.Object e)
        Inserts the element into the collection. Unless otherwise specified, this method will always put the element at the "end" of the collection, if that is possible. Some collections do not allow things like duplicates or null elements. They should document such cases and what exceptions will be thrown.
        Parameters:
        e - element to add to the collection

      • remove

        void remove(java.lang.Object o)
        Removes the element from the collection. Unless otherwise specified, this method will always remove the "first" instance of this element, if that is possible.
        Parameters:
        o - element to remove from the collection

      • containsAll

        Returns:

      • addAll

      • removeAll

        void removeAll(Collection c)

      • retainAll

        void retainAll(Collection c)
        Removes from this collection all of its elements that are not contained in c.
        Parameters:
        c - collection of elements to ensure are contained

      • clear

        void clear()
        Removes every element in this collection. After this method is called, provided nothing else is called, by convention isEmpty() will return true.
